<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910111-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>910111-0020.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Westinghouse Electric Corp.:   Four Suspended in Alarm   Tampering at Nuclear Plant</HL><DATE>01/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   WX</CO><IN>ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)</IN><LP>   Westinghouse Hanford Co. said it suspended four employeesindefinitely without pay in connection with an intentionalsilencing of an alarm panel at a nuclear facility.   The company, a unit of Westinghouse Electric Corp., saidlast week an engineer found a paper clip wedged in the alarmpanel, preventing six alarms from sounding. The alarm was atan evaporator, used to reduce the volume of nuclear wastestored in underground tanks. The facility has been shut downsince the mid-1980s, but still houses equipment used tomonitor some underground nuclear waste storage tanks.</LP><TEXT>   Westinghouse said it was the third such incident atHanford in less than six months. Investigations of the otherincidents didn't determine who was responsible or why thetampering happened. The company, which manages facilities forthe Department of Energy, is continuing its investigation.</TEXT></DOC>